 Farming-based Money flow 36 (2007) 253-270 
 
 Farming-based trade (easing government rules) and money-based development: 
 the role of downstream market power 
 Richard J. Church assistanta , Ian Sheldonb,a-- , Steve McCorristonc , Humei Wangd 
 a Department 
 
 of Farming-based and useful thing/valuable supply Money flow and Giannini Foundation of Farming-based Money flow, University of California, Davis, CA 95616, USA 
 b Department of Farming-based, (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth), and Development Money flow, Ohio State University, Columbus, OH 43210, USA 
 c School of Business and Money flow, University of Exeter, Exeter EX4 4PU, UK 
 d California Department of Health Services, Sacramento, CA 95899, USA 
 Received 5 July 2005; received in changed form 14 April 2006; accepted 10 August 2006 
 
 Abstract 
 A model is developed to show the (up and down) linked and (mainly studied) nature of developed-country food markets. This model is then 
 limit/guidelineized and used to test out the effects of different food market structures on the benefits to developing-country exporters of farming-based 
 valuable things from trade (easing government rules) by developed countries. Results show that even small departures from perfect competition 
 can cause much of the benefits from trade (easing government rules) to flow to marketing firms instead of producers in the developing country. The distributional 
 effects under downstream market power differ significantly from the perfectly competitive case and may result, somewhat surprisingly, in 
 developing countries receiving a lower share of the total value added within the food chain as trade reform happens. 
 JEL Classification: F12, F13, O12 
 Keywords: Developing countries; Oligopoly; Oligopsony; Trade (easing government rules); Up-and-down market structure 
 
 1. Introduction 
 The Doha Round of trade (back-and-forth conversations to agree on something) in the World Trade Organization (WTO) has been labeled the "development round," 
 a important part of which will be increasing developing countries' 
 access to developed-country markets (Anderson and Martin, 
 2005). This process will involve the reduction of taxes/import taxes on farming-based valuable things, given that many developing countries 
 are still major farming-based exporters and that farming still 
 accounts for a large share of GDP, especially in the poorest 
 developing countries. However, in terms of the possible benefits to developing countries, there are two connected issues. 
 First, recognizing the (up and down) linked nature of the food chain 
 among farm-related, food processing and retailing, the increasing 
 combining of the food industry in developed countries may 
 influence the importance of the benefits that developing countries receive from increased market access. Second, in terms 
 of the total value of the product that reaches people, the 
 raw farming-based part usually represents a small share. 
 This has caused many in developing countries as well as in 
 a-- Corresponding author. Tel.: (614)-292-2194. 
 E-mail address: sheldon.1@osu.edu (Ian Sheldon). 
 
 c 2007 International Association of Farming-based Money-flow experts 
 
 international institutions to fight for (getting involved with different types of things; not sticking with only one thing) in developing countries, involving the processing of and adding value to 
 the raw farming-based valuable thing (UNCTAD, 2002a). 
 These issues can be related clearly to the wider popular 
 debate about (when lots of countries communicate and talk with each other). First, concerns have been expressed 
 that increasing concentration of the worldwide  food system harms 
 producers of export valuable things very important to many developing 
 countries. For example, African countries such as Burundi, 
 Ethiopia, Rwanda, and Uganda are highly dependent on exports of coffee, yet all have faced a significant decline in real 
 prices over the past few years. 1 At the same time, in key export 
 markets such as Europe and the United States, worldwide  coffee 
 buyers, roasters, and stores, who in total account for almost 
 60% of the share of final sales value of coffee, have benefited 
 from lower coffee bean prices (Oxfam, 2001). 2 Second, tax/import tax 
 1 Over the period 1998-2001, real coffee prices fell by 50%. As a result, for a 
 country such as Ethiopia, where coffee represented 67% of the value of exports 
 in 1998, the decline in world coffee prices cost Ethiopia US$_$ 300 million in 
 export money/money income, equal to 50% of its once-a-year export earnings (Oxfam, 2001). 
 2 All three parts/areas are ruled by a small number of firms. For example, in 
 1995, 10 firms accounted for 62% of worldwide  coffee bean trade, while in 1998, 
 five firms accounted for 58%of sales of roasted coffee in the (related to Europe) market 
 (Fitter and Kaplinsky, 2001). 
 
 254 
 
 R. J. Church assistant et al. / Farming-based Money flow 36 (2007) 253-270 
 
 reduction and market access go right to the heart of the debate 
 over whether smallholder farmers in developing countries will 
 truly benefit from (when lots of countries communicate and talk with each other). On the one hand, development 
 (services businesses/government units) such as the World Bank (2003), and NGOs such as Oxfam, have argued a lot that removal of trade twisting/lying about 
 farming-based policies in both the developed and developing countries has the "potential to act as a powerful helper for poorness 
 reduction" (Oxfam, 2003, p. 7) in the developing countries. On 
 the other hand, people (who say bad things or give opinions) of (when lots of countries communicate and talk with each other) have argued that it may 
 create negative effects for developing-country farmers. 
 The Mozambique cashew nut part/area provides a good example 
 of this debate. In the early 1990s, Mozambique removed taxes 
 on the export of raw cashews in response to guidance from the 
 World Bank. The World Bank (1995) forecast that cashew nut 
 farmers' incomes would increase between US$_$ 17.4 and 27.9 
 million in the first 2 years of the reform. However, McMillan 
 et al. (2002) report that the actual gains to cashew nut farmers 
 were only US$_$ 5.3 million. At the same time, city-based  unemployment increased as labor released from cashew nut processing 
 did not move into other activities. This case became a "cause 
 cÂ´el`ebre" for the antiglobalization movement, and a focus for 
 attacking World Bank policies (McMillan et al., 2002, p. 1). 
 What the World Bank ignores in its guesses was that the 
 hit/effect of reform in the Mozambique cashew nut part/area was in 
 large part influenced by the (features/ qualities/ traits) of the downstream 
 part/area which cashew nut farmers supplied. As McMillan et al. 
 (2002) note, traders downstream from farmers are competitive 
 in selling cashews, but have buying (monopsony) power in the 
 (instance of buying something for money) of cashews. As a result, even though export prices 
 for raw cashew nuts did increase, as (stated or said earlier) by explanation, export traders (taken/took by force)/(taken/took control of) a (compared to other things) large share of the benefits 
 from removal of the export tax, reducing the income gains to 
 farmers. 3 
 Therefore, in carefully studying the hit/effect of trade (easing government rules) on 
 developing countries, it is necessary to understand the up-and-down linkages that describe food markets in many developed 
 countries. We argue in this article that the modern food marketing system in many businesses is most appropriately seen as a (one after the other) oligopoly/oligopsony structure, with 
 developing-country exporters of raw valuable things entering at 
 the first stage, and show that the hint/result/effect of reducing taxes/import taxes or export taxes under this structure may be much different 
 in importance from that suggested by models that assume perfect 
 competition. More than that, the distributional effects will also differ 
 relative to the perfectly competitive case and may result, somewhat surprisingly, in developing countries receiving a lower 
 share of the total value added within the food chain as trade 
 reform happens. 
 3 Another example is Ivory Coast cocoa market (easing government rules) (Wilcox and 
 Abbott, 2004). Before (easing government rules), para-statal marketing boards controlled 
 all levels of marketing of cocoa beans and also taxed cocoa bean exports. 
 (easing government rules) has resulted in backward integration by huge company cocoa 
 processor-exporters who now take (prisoner) by force a part of/amount of the rents (before that/before now) collected 
 as export taxes. 
 
 We develop this theme by first presenting some (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) on 
 the structure of the food chain in developed (processes of people making, selling, and buying things), focusing specifically upon the (related to Europe) Union (EU) and the United 
 States. We then develop, in Section 3, a model that describes the (up and down) linked nature of developed-country food 
 markets. The model is based on a market setting in which a 
 first (or most important) farming-based product such as coffee is exported from 
 a developing (process of people making, selling, and buying things), and is then processed and sold in a 
 developed (process of people making, selling, and buying things). 4 The market structure in the developed 
 (process of people making, selling, and buying things) features independent processing and retailing parts/areas, 
 both of which may show market power. Next, in Section 4, 
 we get the effects/results/suggestions of different combinations of market 
 structures in the processing and/or the retailing part/area on total 
 market extra, and the distribution of benefits from reducing 
 a per-unit tax/import tax among people in the developed (process of people making, selling, and buying things), 
 developing-country producers, and marketers (processors and 
 stores), given price-taking behavior by farm producers and 
 people but possible oligopoly and/or oligopsony power exercised by the marketing part/area. Some extensions are organized and listed 
 in Section 5, and in Section 6 we summarize and end/decide. 
 2. Market structure of the food part/area in developed 
 (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) 
 As noted, the food industry is usually highly (focused one's effort/increased/mainly studied) in 
 developed countries at both the retail and processing stages and, 
 further, concentration is rising over time. This is also becoming 
 a (feature/ quality/ trait) of the food part/area in some developing countries. 
 By way of illustration, we focus specifically on these parts/areas in 
 the United States and the EU. 
 2.1. Food processing 
 In the United States, the top-20 food-manufacturing firms 
 accounted for 37% of value added in 1997, while the top-20 
 drink- and tobacco-manufacturing firms accounted for 79% 
 of value added (U.S. (official count of everyone who lives in a country, city, etc.)  Bureau, 2001). Using more disaggregated data at the four-digit SITC level, the average four-firm 
 concentration ratio (CR4) in U.S. food manufacturing was about 
 76% in 1997, ranging from 62% in sugar cane mills to 98% in 
 cigarettes. 
 Average seller concentration in the EU is higher than in the 
 United States, ranging from an average CR3 of 55% in Germany to 89% in Ireland, with an average CR3 across nine EU 
 countries of 67% (Cotterill, 1999). As in the United States, 
 these averages hide some high levels of seller concentration for 
 clearly stated/particular products in each EU country, especially baby foods, 
 canned soup, pet food, and coffee. While seller concentration 
 at the product level is high in many individual EU country markets, there are few examples of firms that rule sales across 
 EU countries as a whole (Cotterill, 1999). 
 4 
 
 As the focus of this article is on gains to developing country exporters 
 from trade (easing government rules), we abstract from any hits/effects on developed country 
 farming-based parts/areas. 
 
