 2.3. Industry combining 
 An added feature of market structure in the food industry 
 over the last few years has been combining through mergers and 
 purchases, which has added/has given to increasing concentration. 
 Domestic mergers and purchases in the food part/area doubled 
 between 1990 and 2002 (McCorriston et al., 2004). More than that, 
 international mergers and purchases have also been increasing 
 significantly. For example, EU-based stores such as Royal 
 Ahold and Sainsbury have expanded into U.S. markets, and 
 Wal-Mart has expanded into the EU. As a result, food retailing 
 is becoming more and more huge company with three food stores 
 Wal-Mart, Carrefour, and Royal Ahold now appearing in the 
 world's top-100 huge company corporations (UNCTAD, 2002b). 
 Although the high and rising concentration in the food part/area 
 is not a doubtful point, evidence on the extent of 
 the actual exercise of manufacturer and store market power 
 in developed-country food parts/areas is rather mixed. Surveys of 
 the recent scientific work by Church assistant (2000), Church assistant and Lavoie 
 (2001), and Sheldon and Sperling (2003) show/tell about (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) of 
 only modest departures from perfect competition for a wide 
 range of products in the food manufacturing/processing part/area. 
 Table 1 summarizes results of market power guesses for a 
 broad range of businesses. The possible range for the market 
 power limits/guidelines in the table is from 0 (perfect competition) to 
 1 ((one company that controls too much) or monopsony). Although a few guesses are in 
 the area of 0.5 (market power equal to that of a (group of things that are all pretty much the same) Cournot rule (by two people) or duopsony) or higher, most are much 
 lower--0.25 (the market power equal of a (group of things that are all pretty much the same) 
 four-firm Cournot oligopoly or oligopsony) or less. 
