 3.2. Market power at (one after the other) market stages 
 Now we think about/believe pictures/situations in which stores in the importing country may exercise oligopoly power over people 
 and domestic processors may exercise oligopsony power 
 over farmers in getting the raw product, and, also, 
 processor-store interactions may be seen as (not totally pure/not totally correct) competition. We think about/believe two other choice cases for 
 the processor-store interactions. The first involves processor oligopoly power and store price taking in the processor- 
 store interactions ((one after the other) oligopoly), and the second 
 involves store oligopsony power and processor price taking 
 ((one after the other) oligopsony) in the processor-store interactions. 
 The case in which both stores and processors attempt to exercise market power in their back and forth/equal between people interactions must be studied 
 within a (related to arriving at an agreement) (surrounding conditions), which is beyond the extent of/the range of 
 the present study. 12 
 It should be noted that the exercise of market power at (one after the other) up-and-down stages in a market chain represents a market 
 failure that may, in way of thinking/basic truth/rule, be corrected through up-and-down coordination across market stages. Especially, the solutions we 
 bring up show the well-known "double-(making something unimportant)" problem noted first by Spengler (1950). If firms can coordinate (up and down), they can eliminate the double-(making something unimportant) 
 problem and increase the total amount of (money made/good things received) to be shared 
 between them. Katz (1989) remains a good summary reference on the tools of up-and-down control. Our results in this 
 subsection should, this way, be understood/explained to apply in settings in 
 which instruments of up-and-down control are either unavailable, 
 (way too much) expensive to put into use, or illegal under winning/most common 
 (related to preventing one company from becoming too powerful) laws, e.g., Viscusi et al. (2000). If manufacturers 
 and stores with market power can solve their doublemarginalization problem, the results of the previous subsection 
 apply. 
