 understate current levels of market power. Also, Church assistant 
 (2000) has argued that the limits of the existing scientific 
 books probably serve on balance to understate the extent 
 of market power. For example, this end/end result would apply 
 to (i) analysis of inappropriately broad product markets, (ii) 
 
 failure to account for the possibility of market power upstream 
 or downstream from the stage being carefully studied, and (iii) failure 
 to account properly for technical change and/or (processes of people making, selling, and buying things) of 
 scale in costs. 
